Section 41. Rights and Obligations of the Person Held Liable

(1) The person held liable has the following rights:

1) to acquaint himself or herself with the materials of the administrative offence case;
2) to participate in the examination of the administrative offence case;
3) to provide explanations;
4) to use a language he or she understands and to use the assistance of an interpreter;
5) to know for what offence he or she is held liable;
6) to submit evidence;
7) to appeal the adopted decision;
8) to exercise defence with the assistance of a chosen defender;
9) to withdraw a complaint or request submitted by a defender.

(2) The person held liable has the following obligations:

1) to appear at the specified time and place;
2) not to obstruct the administrative process;
3) to notify about any change of address;
4) to cease the unlawful conduct;
5) to comply with any procedural coercive measures applied.

(4) A detained person has the right:

1) to invite a defender;
2) to request that his or her relatives, educational institution or employer be informed of the detention. In the case of a minor, the representative must be informed;
3) to become acquainted with the detention protocol and to receive information on his or her rights and obligations;
4) to express his or her opinion on the justification for the detention.

(5) A person may be detained for no longer than four hours. The period of detention shall be counted from the moment of actual detention. If the person is under the influence of alcohol or other intoxicating substances, the period shall be counted from the time when the person is able to adequately perceive what is happening.

(6) The detention protocol shall be notified to the person concerned.

(1) The following circumstances mitigate administrative liability:

1) the person held liable has admitted and regretted the offence;
2) the person has voluntarily compensated the loss or eliminated the damage caused;
3) the offence was committed under strong emotional distress or due to serious personal or family circumstances;
4) the person voluntarily reported the offence before it was discovered;
5) the offence was committed under provocation by the victim’s unlawful or immoral conduct;
6) the offence was committed by a pregnant woman or a woman caring for a child under one year of age.

(2) Other circumstances may also be recognised as mitigating.

The following circumstances aggravate administrative liability:

1) the unlawful act was continued despite an authorised official’s request to cease it;
2) the offence involved a minor engaged by an adult;
3) the offence was committed during a natural disaster or other extraordinary circumstances;
4) the offence was committed under the influence of alcohol, narcotic or other intoxicating substances;
5) the motive of the offence was hatred towards a person’s race, religion, nationality or other clearly identifiable features;
6) the offence was committed by a group of persons.
